<p>
  PDFs created from phone photos or low-quality scanners often look washed out — grey backgrounds,
  soft text, uneven lighting. You need them to look like they came from a proper flatbed scanner.
  This guide shows you how to clean up every page automatically, for free, without any software.
</p>

<h2>The Problem with Phone-Photo PDFs</h2>

<p>When you photograph a document with your phone and convert it to a PDF, you get:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Uneven background — shadows in corners, yellow/warm cast from room light</li>
  <li>Soft or blurry text from camera focus or motion</li>
  <li>Grey paper instead of white — hard to read and visually cluttered</li>
  <li>Low contrast — dark text and dark background blend together</li>
</ul>

<p>
  A proper scan fixes all of these. The <a href="/pdfwonder/pdf-scan-enhance">PDF Scan Enhancer</a>
  replicates what scanner software does: grayscale conversion, automatic level adjustment,
  contrast boost, and edge sharpening — applied to every page in one click.
</p>

<h2>How to Enhance a Scanned PDF (Step by Step)</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Open the <a href="/pdfwonder/pdf-scan-enhance">PDF Scan Enhancer</a>.</li>
  <li>Drop your PDF in or click to browse.</li>
  <li>A preview of page 1 loads — click <strong>Enhanced (Page 1 preview)</strong> tab to see the effect.</li>
  <li>Choose a preset: <strong>Document Clean</strong> (recommended), <strong>Soft Scan</strong>, or <strong>Photocopy</strong>.</li>
  <li>Adjust sliders if needed (Brightness, Contrast, Background Clip, Sharpen).</li>
  <li>Click <strong>Apply to All Pages & Download PDF</strong>.</li>
  <li>A progress bar shows each page being processed. The enhanced PDF downloads automatically when done.</li>
</ol>

