<h2>Understanding the Three Presets</h2>

<h3>Document Clean (default)</h3>
<p>
  Applies 2% histogram clipping, moderate contrast, and edge sharpening.
  Best for typed text, printed documents, answer sheets, and books photographed under normal indoor light.
  The most common choice for PDFs made from phone photos.
</p>

<h3>Soft Scan</h3>
<p>
  Lower contrast and no sharpening. Preserves fine pencil marks, handwriting, and mid-tones.
  Use this for handwritten notes, pencil sketches, or lightly printed text where the aggressive
  Document Clean preset makes fine strokes disappear.
</p>

<h3>Photocopy</h3>
<p>
  Maximum contrast — bold black text, pure white background.
  Some fine detail is lost. Best for documents that will be printed or faxed,
  or PDFs where the text contrast needs to be as high as possible for OCR software.
</p>

<h2>How the Enhancement Works</h2>

<p>Each page goes through four steps:</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <strong>Render at 144 DPI</strong> — PDF.js renders each page at 2× the base PDF resolution
    (72 pt/inch × 2 = 144 DPI), producing a crisp raster image of each page.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Grayscale conversion</strong> — colour information is discarded using
    the standard luminance formula, removing colour cast from warm light or tinted paper.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Auto-levels</strong> — the tool analyses the pixel histogram and
    clips the darkest and brightest N% of pixels before stretching the remaining range to fill 0–255.
    This is what removes shadows and makes the background white even under uneven lighting.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Contrast boost and optional sharpening</strong> — a contrast factor formula
    increases tonal separation between text and paper, and an unsharp mask
    (2-pass box blur) makes text edges crisp.
  </li>
</ol>

<p>
  The enhanced pages are embedded as JPEG images into a new PDF using pdf-lib.
  The output file dimensions match the original PDF exactly.
</p>

<h2>Tips for Best Results</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Shoot in good light:</strong> Even with auto-levels, extreme shadows from a single lamp are harder to remove. Photograph near a window or under ceiling lights.</li>
  <li><strong>Increase Background Clip to 3–5%</strong> for PDFs taken under warm artificial light — this more aggressively whitens the background at the cost of slightly clipping very light text.</li>
  <li><strong>Use Soft Scan for handwriting</strong> — high contrast can cause thin pencil strokes to disappear.</li>
  <li><strong>Check page 1 carefully</strong> before clicking Apply — if shadows are still visible, increase the clip slider until the background looks clean in the preview.</li>
</ul>

